95  /*
96  If the local implementation of cbrt() below is inadequate due to the
97  ldexp, frexp calls that may not exist, use pow(x,1/3) instead. Define

104  go_real go_cbrt(go_real x)
105  {
106  if (x < 0.0) {
107  return (go_real) -pow((double) -x, 1.0/3.0);

114  /*
115  cbrt.c
116 
117  Cube root function
118 
119  Adapted from Cephes Math Library Release 2.8: June, 2000
120  Copyright 1984, 1991, 2000 by Stephen L. Moshier
121  */
122 
123  static double CBRT2 = 1.2599210498948731647672;
124  static double CBRT4 = 1.5874010519681994747517;
125  static double CBRT2I = 0.79370052598409973737585;
126  static double CBRT4I = 0.62996052494743658238361;
127 
128 #include <math.h> /* frexp(), ldexp() */
129 
130  static double cbrt(double x)
131  {
132  int e, rem, sign;
133  double z;
134 
135  if (x == 0) {
136  return x;
137  }
138 
139  if (x > 0) {
140  sign = 1;
141  } else {
142  sign = -1;
143  x = -x;
144  }
145 
146  z = x;
147 
148  /* extract power of 2, leaving mantissa between 0.5 and 1 */
149  x = frexp(x, &e);
150 
151  /* Approximate cube root of number between .5 and 1,
152  peak relative error = 9.2e-6 */
153  x = (((-1.3466110473359520655053e-1 * x
154  + 5.4664601366395524503440e-1) * x
155  - 9.5438224771509446525043e-1) * x
156  + 1.1399983354717293273738e0) * x + 4.0238979564544752126924e-1;
157 
158  /* exponent divided by 3 */
159  if (e >= 0) {
160  rem = e;
161  e /= 3;
162  rem -= 3 * e;
163  if (rem == 1) {
164  x *= CBRT2;
165  } else if (rem == 2) {
166  x *= CBRT4;
167  }
168  } else {
169  /* argument less than 1 */
170  e = -e;
171  rem = e;
172  e /= 3;
173  rem -= 3 * e;
174  if (rem == 1)
175  x *= CBRT2I;
176  else if (rem == 2)
177  x *= CBRT4I;
178  e = -e;
179  }
180 
181  /* multiply by power of 2 */
182  x = ldexp(x, e);
183 
184  /* Newton iteration */
185  x -= (x - (z / (x * x))) * 0.33333333333333333333;
186  x -= (x - (z / (x * x))) * 0.33333333333333333333;
187 
188  if (sign < 0) {
189  x = -x;
190  }
191 
192  return x;
193  }

207  go_result go_cart_sph_convert(const go_cart *v, go_sph *s)
208  {
209  go_real r;
210 
211  s->theta = atan2(v->y, v->x);
212  r = sqrt(go_sq(v->x) + go_sq(v->y) + go_sq(v->z));
213  s->r = r;
214  if (GO_TRAN_SMALL(r)) {
215  s->phi = 0;
216  } else {
217  s->phi = acos(v->z / r);
218  }
219 
220  return GO_RESULT_OK;
221  }

283  go_result go_rvec_quat_convert(const go_rvec *r, go_quat *q)
284  {
285  go_cart vec;
286  go_cart uvec;
287  go_real mag;
288  go_real sh;
289 
290  vec.x = r->x;
291  vec.y = r->y;
292  vec.z = r->z;
293 
294  if (GO_RESULT_OK != go_cart_unit(&vec, &uvec)) {
295  /* a zero vector */
296  q->s = 1;
297  q->x = q->y = q->z = 0;
298  return GO_RESULT_OK;
299  }
300 
301  (void) go_cart_mag(&vec, &mag);
302 
303  go_sincos(0.5 * mag, &sh, &(q->s));
304 
305  if (q->s >= 0) {
306  q->x = uvec.x * sh;
307  q->y = uvec.y * sh;
308  q->z = uvec.z * sh;
309  } else {
310  q->s = -q->s;
311  q->x = -uvec.x * sh;
312  q->y = -uvec.y * sh;
313  q->z = -uvec.z * sh;
314  }
315 
316  return GO_RESULT_OK;
317  }

319  go_result go_rvec_mat_convert(const go_rvec *r, go_mat *m)
320  {
321  go_cart vec;
322  go_cart uvec;
323  go_real s, c, omc;
324  go_real mag;
325 
326  vec.x = r->x;
327  vec.y = r->y;
328  vec.z = r->z;
329 
330  if (GO_RESULT_OK != go_cart_unit(&vec, &uvec)) {
331  /* a zero vector */
332  m->x.x = 1, m->y.x = 0, m->z.x = 0;
333  m->x.y = 0, m->y.y = 1, m->z.y = 0;
334  m->x.z = 0, m->y.z = 0, m->z.z = 1;
335  return GO_RESULT_OK;
336  }
337 
338  (void) go_cart_mag(&vec, &mag);
339 
340  go_sincos(mag, &s, &c);
341  omc = 1 - c;
342 
343  m->x.x = c + go_sq(uvec.x) * omc;
344  m->y.x = -uvec.z * s + uvec.x * uvec.y * omc;
345  m->z.x = uvec.y * s + uvec.x * uvec.z * omc;
346 
347  m->x.y = uvec.z * s + uvec.y * uvec.x * omc;
348  m->y.y = c + go_sq(uvec.y) * omc;
349  m->z.y = -uvec.x * s + uvec.y * uvec.z * omc;
350 
351  m->x.z = -uvec.y * s + uvec.z * uvec.x * omc;
352  m->y.z = uvec.x * s + uvec.z * uvec.y * omc;
353  m->z.z = c + go_sq(uvec.z) * omc;
354 
355  return GO_RESULT_OK;
356  }

391  go_result go_quat_rvec_convert(const go_quat *q, go_rvec *r)
392  {
393  go_real sh;
394  go_real mag;
395 
396  sh = sqrt(go_sq(q->x) + go_sq(q->y) + go_sq(q->z));
397 
398  if (GO_ROT_SMALL(sh)) {
399  r->x = 0;
400  r->y = 0;
401  r->z = 0;
402  } else {
403  mag = 2 * atan2(sh, q->s) / sh;
404  r->x = mag * q->x;
405  r->y = mag * q->y;
406  r->z = mag * q->z;
407  }
408 
409  return GO_RESULT_OK;
410  }

412  go_result go_quat_mat_convert(const go_quat *q, go_mat *m)
413  {
414  /* from space book where e1=q->x e2=q->y e3=q->z e4=q->s */
415  m->x.x = 1 - 2 * (go_sq(q->y) + go_sq(q->z));
416  m->y.x = 2 * (q->x * q->y - q->z * q->s);
417  m->z.x = 2 * (q->z * q->x + q->y * q->s);
418 
419  m->x.y = 2 * (q->x * q->y + q->z * q->s);
420  m->y.y = 1 - 2 * (go_sq(q->z) + go_sq(q->x));
421  m->z.y = 2 * (q->y * q->z - q->x * q->s);
422 
423  m->x.z = 2 * (q->z * q->x - q->y * q->s);
424  m->y.z = 2 * (q->y * q->z + q->x * q->s);
425  m->z.z = 1 - 2 * (go_sq(q->x) + go_sq(q->y));
426 
427  return GO_RESULT_OK;
428  }

460  go_result go_mat_rvec_convert(const go_mat *m, go_rvec *r)
461  {
462  go_quat q;
463  go_result retval;

470 
471  /*
472  from space book:
473 
474  e1 = (c32 - c23) / 4*e4
475  e2 = (c13 - c31) / 4*e4
476  e3 = (c21 - c12) / 4*e4
477  e4 = sqrt(1 + c11 + c22 + c33) / 2
478 
479  if e4 == 0
480  e1 = sqrt(1 + c11 - c33 - c22) / 2
481  e2 = sqrt(1 + c22 - c33 - c11) / 2
482  e3 = sqrt(1 + c33 - c11 - c22) / 2
483 
484  to determine whether to take the positive or negative sqrt value
485  since e4 == 0 indicates a 180* rotation then (0 x y z) = (0 -x -y -z).
486  Thus some generalities can be used:
487  1) find which of e1, e2, or e3 has the largest magnitude and leave it pos
488  2) if e1 is largest then
489  if c21 < 0 then take the negative for e2
490  if c31 < 0 then take the negative for e3
491  3) else if e2 is largest then
492  if c21 < 0 then take the negative for e1
493  if c32 < 0 then take the negative for e3
494  4) else if e3 is larget then
495  if c31 < 0 then take the negative for e1
496  if c32 < 0 then take the negative for e2
497 
498  Note: c21 in the space book is m.x.y in this C code
499  */
500  go_result go_mat_quat_convert(const go_mat *m, go_quat *q)
501  {
502  go_real discr;
503  go_real a;
504 
505  if (! go_mat_is_norm(m)) {
506  return GO_RESULT_NORM_ERROR;
507  }
508 
509  discr = 1.0 + m->x.x + m->y.y + m->z.z;
510  if (discr < 0.0) discr = 0.0; /* give sqrt some slack for tiny negs */
511 
512  q->s = 0.5 * sqrt(discr);
513 
514  if (GO_ROT_SMALL(q->s)) {
515  q->s = 0;
516  discr = 1.0 + m->x.x - m->y.y - m->z.z;
517  if (discr < 0.0) discr = 0.0;
518  q->x = sqrt(discr) / 2.0;
519  discr = 1.0 + m->y.y - m->x.x - m->z.z;
520  if (discr < 0.0) discr = 0.0;
521  q->y = sqrt(discr) / 2.0;
522  discr = 1.0 + m->z.z - m->y.y - m->x.x;
523  if (discr < 0.0) discr = 0.0;
524  q->z = sqrt(discr) / 2.0;
525 
526  if (q->x > q->y && q->x > q->z) {
527  if (m->x.y < 0.0) {
528  q->y *= -1;
529  }
530  if (m->x.z < 0.0) {
531  q->z *= -1;
532  }
533  } else if (q->y > q->z) {
534  if (m->x.y < 0.0) {
535  q->x *= -1;
536  }
537  if (m->y.z < 0.0) {
538  q->z *= -1;
539  }
540  } else {
541  if (m->x.z < 0.0) {
542  q->x *= -1;
543  }
544  if (m->y.z < 0.0) {
545  q->y *= -1;
546  }
547  }
548  } else {
549  q->x = (m->y.z - m->z.y) / (a = 4 * q->s);
550  q->y = (m->z.x - m->x.z) / a;
551  q->z = (m->x.y - m->y.x) / a;
552  }
553 
554  return go_quat_norm(q, q);
555  }

557  go_result go_mat_zyz_convert(const go_mat *m, go_zyz *zyz)
558  {
559  zyz->y = atan2(sqrt(go_sq(m->x.z) + go_sq(m->y.z)), m->z.z);
560 
561  if (GO_ROT_SMALL(zyz->y)) {
562  zyz->z = 0;
563  zyz->y = 0; /* force Y to 0 */
564  zyz->zp = atan2(-m->y.x, m->x.x);
565  } else if (GO_ROT_CLOSE(zyz->y, GO_PI)) {
566  zyz->z = 0;
567  zyz->y = GO_PI; /* force Y to 180 */
568  zyz->zp = atan2(m->y.x, -m->x.x);
569  } else {
570  zyz->z = atan2(m->z.y, m->z.x);
571  zyz->zp = atan2(m->y.z, -m->x.z);
572  }
573 
574  return GO_RESULT_OK;
575  }

582  zyx->z = 0;

588  zyx->x = atan2(-m->y.x, m->y.y);
589  } else {
590  zyx->z = atan2(m->x.y, m->x.x);
591  zyx->x = atan2(m->y.z, m->z.z);

617  go_result go_mat_rpy_convert(const go_mat *m, go_rpy *rpy)
618  {

620

627  rpy->p = -GO_PI_2; /* force it */
628  rpy->y = 0;
629  } else {
630  rpy->r = atan2(m->y.z, m->z.z);
631  rpy->y = atan2(m->x.y, m->x.x);

637  go_result go_zyz_rvec_convert(const go_zyz *zyz, go_rvec *r)

657  go_result go_zyz_mat_convert(const go_zyz *zyz, go_mat *m)
658  {
659  go_real sa, sb, sg;
660  go_real ca, cb, cg;
661 
662  sa = sin(zyz->z);
663  sb = sin(zyz->y);
664  sg = sin(zyz->zp);
665 
666  ca = cos(zyz->z);
667  cb = cos(zyz->y);
668  cg = cos(zyz->zp);
669 
670  m->x.x = ca * cb * cg - sa * sg;
671  m->y.x = -ca * cb * sg - sa * cg;
672  m->z.x = ca * sb;
673 
674  m->x.y = sa * cb * cg + ca * sg;
675  m->y.y = -sa * cb * sg + ca * cg;
676  m->z.y = sa * sb;
677 
678  m->x.z = -sb * cg;
679  m->y.z = sb * sg;
680  m->z.z = cb;
681 
682  return GO_RESULT_OK;
683  }

777  go_result go_xyz_mat_convert(const go_xyz *xyz, go_mat *m)
778  {
779  go_real s1, s2, s3;
780  go_real c1, c2, c3;
781 
782  s1 = sin(xyz->x);
783  s2 = sin(xyz->y);
784  s3 = sin(xyz->z);
785 
786  c1 = cos(xyz->x);
787  c2 = cos(xyz->y);
788  c3 = cos(xyz->z);
789 
790  /* | m.x.x m.y.x m.z.x | */
791  /* go_mat m = | m.x.y m.y.y m.z.y | */
792  /* | m.x.z m.y.z m.z.z | */
793 
794  m->x.x = c2*c3;
795  m->y.x = -c2*s3;
796  m->z.x = s2;
797 
798  m->x.y = c1*s3 + s1*s2*c3;
799  m->y.y = c1*c3 - s1*s2*s3;
800  m->z.y = -c2*s1;
801 
802  m->x.z = s1*s3 - c1*s2*c3;
803  m->y.z = s1*c3 + c1*s2*s3;
804  m->z.z = c1*c2;
805 
806  return GO_RESULT_OK;
807  }

997  go_result go_cart_cart_cross(const go_cart *v1, const go_cart *v2,
998  go_cart *vout)
999  {
1000  go_cart cp1, cp2;
1001 
1002  cp1 = *v1;
1003  cp2 = *v2;
1004 
1005  vout->x = cp1.y * cp2.z - cp1.z * cp2.y;
1006  vout->y = cp1.z * cp2.x - cp1.x * cp2.z;
1007  vout->z = cp1.x * cp2.y - cp1.y * cp2.x;
1008 
1009  return GO_RESULT_OK;
1010  }

1027  {

1032  parallel if v1 dot v2 = mag v1 * mag v2, or more efficiently,
1033  sq(v1 dot v2) = magsq v1 * magsq v2
1034  */

1036  go_cart_cart_dot(v1, v2, &dot);
1037  go_cart_magsq(v1, &magsq1);
1038  go_cart_magsq(v2, &magsq2);

1041  }

1102  go_result go_cart_unit(const go_cart *v, go_cart *vout)
1103  {
1104  go_real size = sqrt(go_sq(v->x) + go_sq(v->y) + go_sq(v->z));
1105 
1106  if (GO_TRAN_SMALL(size)) {
1107  vout->x = GO_INF;
1108  vout->y = GO_INF;
1109  vout->z = GO_INF;
1110 
1111  return GO_RESULT_NORM_ERROR;
1112  }
1113 
1114  size = 1.0 / size;
1115 
1116  vout->x = v->x * size;
1117  vout->y = v->y * size;
1118  vout->z = v->z * size;
1119 
1120  return GO_RESULT_OK;
1121  }

1124  {

1126  }
1127 
1128  go_result go_cart_cart_rot(const go_cart *v1,
1129  const go_cart *v2,
1130  go_quat *quat)
1131  {
1132  go_result retval;
1133  go_cart u1;
1134  go_cart u2;
1135  go_cart cross;
1136  go_real mag;
1137  go_real dot;
1138  go_real th;
1139  go_rvec rvec;
1140 
1141  /* unitize the input vectors */
1142  retval = go_cart_unit(v1, &u1);
1143  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
1144  retval = go_cart_unit(v2, &u2);
1145  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
1146  /* and cross the unit vectors to get the mutual normal */
1147  (void) go_cart_cart_cross(&u1, &u2, &cross);
1148  /* the magnitude of the mutual normal is sin theta */
1149  (void) go_cart_mag(&cross, &mag);
1150  th = asin(mag);
1151  /* dot them to get parallel (1) or antiparallel (-1) */
1152  (void) go_cart_cart_dot(&u1, &u2, &dot);
1153  /* make the cross a unit vector so we can theta-ize it */
1154  retval = go_cart_unit(&cross, &cross);
1155 
1156  /* handle aligned vectors */
1157  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) {
1158  /* v1 and v2 are aligned, so th will be zero */
1159  if (dot > 0.0) { /* would be -1 or 1 */
1160  /* parallel */
1161  quat->s = 1.0;
1162  quat->x = quat->y = quat->z = 0.0;
1163  return GO_RESULT_OK;
1164  }
1165  /* else antiparallel - set u2 to be normal to u1,
1166  rotate about it PI rads */
1167  retval = go_cart_normal(&u1, &u2);
1168  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
1169  rvec.x = GO_PI * u2.x;
1170  rvec.y = GO_PI * u2.y;
1171  rvec.z = GO_PI * u2.z;
1172  return go_rvec_quat_convert(&rvec, quat);
1173  }
1174 
1175  /* else not aligned */
1176  if (dot < 0.0) {
1177  th = GO_PI - th;
1178  }
1179  rvec.x = th * cross.x;
1180  rvec.y = th * cross.y;
1181  rvec.z = th * cross.z;
1182  return go_rvec_quat_convert(&rvec, quat);
1183  }

1185  go_result go_cart_cart_proj(const go_cart *v1, const go_cart *v2,
1186  go_cart *vout)
1187  {
1188  go_cart v2u;
1189  go_real d;
1190  go_result retval;
1191 
1192  retval = go_cart_unit(v2, &v2u);
1193  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
1194 
1195  retval = go_cart_cart_dot(v1, &v2u, &d);
1196  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
1197 
1198  return go_cart_scale_mult(&v2u, d, vout);
1199  }

1201  go_result go_cart_plane_proj(const go_cart *v, const go_cart *normal,
1202  go_cart *vout)
1203  {
1204  go_cart par;
1205  go_result retval;
1206 
1207  retval = go_cart_cart_proj(v, normal, &par);
1208  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
1209 
1210  return go_cart_cart_sub(v, &par, vout);
1211  }

1213  go_result go_cart_cart_angle(const go_cart *v1, const go_cart *v2,
1214  go_real *a)
1215  {
1216  go_real dot, m1, m2;
1217 
1218  go_cart_cart_dot(v1, v2, &dot);
1219  go_cart_mag(v1, &m1);
1220  go_cart_mag(v2, &m2);
1221 
1222  if (m1 <= 0. || m2 <= 0.) {
1223  return GO_RESULT_DIV_ERROR;
1224  }
1225 
1226  dot = dot / (m1 * m2);
1227  if (dot > 1.)
1228  dot = 1.;
1229  else if (dot < -1.)
1230  dot = -1.;
1231 
1232  *a = acos(dot);
1233 
1234  return GO_RESULT_OK;
1235  }
1236 
1237  go_result go_cart_normal(const go_cart *v, go_cart *vout)
1238  {
1239  go_cart cart;
1240  go_real min, ymin;
1241 
1242  /* pick the X, Y or Z vector that is most perpendicular to 'v' */
1243  cart.x = 1, cart.y = 0, cart.z = 0; /* start with X */
1244  min = fabs(v->x);
1245  ymin = fabs(v->y);
1246  if (ymin < min) {
1247  min = ymin; /* Y is more perp */
1248  cart.x = 0, cart.y = 1, cart.z = 0;
1249  }
1250  if (fabs(v->z) < min) {
1251  cart.x = 0, cart.y = 0, cart.z = 1;
1252  }
1253 
1254  /* cross the most perp axis vector with 'v' to get a real perp */
1255  go_cart_cart_cross(v, &cart, &cart);
1256 
1257  /* unitize it into 'vout' and return */
1258  return go_cart_unit(&cart, vout);
1259  }
1260 
1261  go_result go_cart_centroid(const go_cart *varray,
1262  go_integer num,
1263  go_cart *centroid)
1264  {
1265  go_integer i;
1266 
1267  if (num < 1) return GO_RESULT_BAD_ARGS;
1268 
1269  centroid->x = varray[0].x;
1270  centroid->y = varray[0].y;
1271  centroid->z = varray[0].z;
1272 
1273  for (i = 1; i < num; i++) {
1274  centroid->x += varray[i].x;
1275  centroid->y += varray[i].y;
1276  centroid->z += varray[i].z;
1277  }
1278 
1279  return go_cart_scale_mult(centroid, 1.0/((go_real) num), centroid);
1280  }
1281 
1282  go_result go_cart_centroidize(const go_cart *vinarray,
1283  go_integer num,
1284  go_cart *centroid,
1285  go_cart *voutarray)
1286  {
1287  go_integer i;
1288  go_result retval;
1289 
1290  retval = go_cart_centroid(vinarray, num, centroid);
1291  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
1292 
1293  for (i = 0; i < num; i++) {
1294  (void) go_cart_cart_sub(&vinarray[i], centroid, &voutarray[i]);
1295  }
1296 
1297  return GO_RESULT_OK;
1298  }
1299 
1300  /*
1301  Another Solution of the Cubic Equation Here is another method of
1302  solving a cubic polynomial equation submitted independently by Paul
1303  A. Torres and Robert A. Warren. It is based on the idea of "completing
1304  the cube," by arranging matters so that three of the four terms are
1305  three of the four terms of a perfect cube.
1306 
1307  Start with the cubic equation
1308 
1309  x3 + ax2 + bx + c = 0.
1310 
1311  If a2 - 3b = 0, then the first three terms are the first three terms
1312  of a perfect cube, namely (x+a/3)3. Then you can "complete the cube"
1313  by subtracting c from both sides and adding the missing term of the
1314  cube a3/27 to both sides. Recalling that b = a2/3, you get
1315 
1316  x3 + ax2 + bx + c = 0,
1317  x3 + ax2 + (a2/3)x + c = 0,
1318  x3 + ax2 + (a2/3)x = -c,
1319  x3 + ax2 + (a2/3)x + a3/27 = a3/27 - c,
1320  (x+a/3)3 = a3/27 - c.
1321 
1322  By taking the cube root of the left side and the three cube roots of
1323  the right side, you get
1324 
1325  x = -a/3 + (a3/27 - c)1/3,
1326  x = -a/3 + (a3/27 - c)1/3(-1+sqrt[-3])/2,
1327  x = -a/3 + (a3/27 - c)1/3(-1-sqrt[-3])/2.
1328 
1329  These are the roots of the cubic equation that were sought.
1330 
1331  If a2 - 3b is nonzero, then proceed as follows. Set x = y + z, where y
1332  is an indeterminate and z is a function of a, b, and c, which will be
1333  found below. Then
1334 
1335  (y+z)3 + a(y+z)2 + b(y+z) + c = 0,
1336  y3 + (3z+a)y2 + (3z2+2az+b)y + (z3+az2+bz+c) = 0,
1337  y3 + dy2 + ey + f = 0,
1338 
1339  where
1340 
1341  d = 3z + a,
1342  e = 3z2 + 2az + b,
1343  f = z3 + az2 + bz + c.
1344 
1345  The first three terms of this equation in y will be those of a perfect
1346  cube if and only if d2 - 3e is zero, which happens if and only if a2 -
1347  3b = 0, which cannot happen in this case, so we seemingly haven't
1348  gained anything. However, the last three terms of this equation in y
1349  will be those of a perfect cube if and only if e2 = 3df, that is if
1350  and only if
1351 
1352  (3z2+2az+b)2 = 3(3z+a)(z3+az2+bz+c),
1353  (a2-3b)z2 + (ab-9c)z + (b2-3ac) = 0,
1354  gz2 + hz + i = 0,
1355 
1356  where
1357 
1358  g = a2 - 3b,
1359  h = ab - 9c,
1360  i = b2 - 3ac.
1361 
1362  Since a2 - 3b is nonzero, g is nonzero, and we have a true quadratic
1363  equation, called the resolvent quadratic. Now we pick z to be a root
1364  of this quadratic equation. If the GCD of z2 + (h/g)z + (i/g) and z3 +
1365  az2 + bz + c as polynomials in z is not 1, then any root of the GCD is
1366  also a root of the original cubic equation in x. Once you have at
1367  least one root, the problem of finding the other roots is reduced to
1368  solving a quadratic or linear equation. If the GCD is 1, then neither
1369  value of z can make f = 0, so we can assume henceforth that f is
1370  nonzero. Either root z of the quadratic will do, but we must choose
1371  one of them. We arbitrarily pick the one with a plus sign in front of
1372  the radical,
1373 
1374  z = (-h+sqrt[h2-4gi])/(2g),
1375  = (9c-ab+sqrt[81c2-54abc+12a3c+12b3-3a2b2])/(2[a2-3b]).
1376 
1377  Set z equal to this value in the equation for y, and divide it by f on
1378  both sides. Then the last three terms of the cubic in y are those of a
1379  perfect cube, namely (ey/[3f]+1)3, so we can complete the cube to
1380  solve it. We do this by subtracting y3/f from both sides, then adding
1381  the missing term of the cubic, (ey/[3f])3 to both sides, obtaining
1382 
1383  (ey/[3f]+1)3 = ([e/(3f)]3-1/f)y3,
1384 
1385  ey/(3f) + 1 = y([e/(3f)]3-1/f)1/3,
1386  ey/(3f) + 1 = y([e/(3f)]3-1/f)1/3(-1+sqrt[-3])/2,
1387  ey/(3f) + 1 = y([e/(3f)]3-1/f)1/3(-1-sqrt[-3])/2,
1388 
1389  y = 3f/[-e+(e3-27f2)1/3],
1390  y = 3f/[-e+(e3-27f2)1/3(-1+sqrt[-3])/2],
1391  y = 3f/[-e+(e3-27f2)1/3(-1-sqrt[-3])/2].
1392 
1393  Now you have the values of y. Add z to each to get the values of x:
1394 
1395  x = z + 3f/[(e3-27f2)1/3-e],
1396  x = z + 3f/[(e3-27f2)1/3(-1+sqrt[-3])/2-e],
1397  x = z + 3f/[(e3-27f2)1/3(-1-sqrt[-3])/2-e].
1398 
1399  These are the roots of the cubic equation that were sought.
1400 
1401  Example: Solve x3 + 6x2 + 9x + 6 = 0.
1402 
1403  a = 6, b = 9, c = 6.
1404 
1405  Then
1406 
1407  d = 3z + 6, e = 3z2 + 12z + 9, f = z3 + 6z2 + 9z + 6.
1408 
1409  Then
1410 
1411  g = a2 - 3b = 36 - 27 = 9,
1412  h = ab - 9c = 54 - 54 = 0,
1413  i = b2 - 3ac = 81 - 108 = -27,
1414 
1415  and the resolvent quadratic is
1416 
1417  9z2 - 27 = 0,
1418  z2 - 3 = 0,
1419  z = sqrt(3).
1420 
1421  Then
1422 
1423  d = 6 + 3 sqrt(3),
1424  e = 18 + 12 sqrt(3),
1425  f = 24 + 12 sqrt(3),
1426 
1427  and the cubic in y is
1428 
1429  y3 + (6+3 sqrt[3])y2 + (18+12 sqrt[3])y + (24+12 sqrt[3]) = 0.
1430 
1431  Then one root is
1432 
1433  y = 3f/[(e3-27f2)1/3-e],
1434  = 3(24+12 sqrt[3])/([18+12 sqrt(3)]3-27[24+12 sqrt(3)]2)1/3-18-12 sqrt[3]),
1435  = (12+6 sqrt[3])/([9+6 sqrt(3)]1/3-3-2 sqrt[3]),
1436  = (6+4 sqrt[3])/([2+sqrt(3)]1/3-2-sqrt[3]).
1437 
1438  After a lot of simplification, you get
1439 
1440  y = -2 - sqrt(3) - (2-sqrt[3])1/3 - (2+sqrt[3])1/3,
1441  x = -2 - (2-sqrt[3])1/3 - (2+sqrt[3])1/3
1442 
1443  (and two other roots).
1444  */
1445 
1446  go_complex go_complex_add(go_complex z1, go_complex z2)
1447  {
1448  go_complex sum;
1449 
1450  sum.re = z1.re + z2.re;
1451  sum.im = z1.im + z2.im;
1452 
1453  return sum;
1454  }
1455 
1456  go_complex go_complex_sub(go_complex z1, go_complex z2)
1457  {
1458  go_complex diff;
1459 
1460  diff.re = z1.re - z2.re;
1461  diff.im = z1.im - z2.im;
1462 
1463  return diff;
1464  }

1466  go_complex go_complex_mult(go_complex z1, go_complex z2)
1467  {
1468  go_complex prod;
1469 
1470  prod.re = (z1.re * z2.re) - (z1.im * z2.im);
1471  prod.im = (z1.re * z2.im) + (z1.im * z2.re);
1472 
1473  return prod;
1474  }

1476  go_complex go_complex_inv(go_complex z, go_result * result)
1477  {
1478  go_complex zout = {0, 0};
1479  go_real denom;
1480 
1481  denom = go_sq(z.re) + go_sq(z.im);
1482  if (denom < GO_REAL_EPSILON) {
1483  if (NULL != result) *result = GO_RESULT_DIV_ERROR;
1484  return zout;
1485  }
1486 
1487  zout.re = z.re, zout.im = -z.im;
1488  if (NULL != result) *result = GO_RESULT_OK;
1489  return go_complex_scale(zout, 1.0 / denom);
1490  }
1491 
1492  go_complex go_complex_div(go_complex z1, go_complex z2, go_result * result)
1493  {
1494  go_complex z2c = {0, 0};
1495  go_real denom;
1496 
1497  denom = go_sq(z2.re) + go_sq(z2.im);
1498  if (denom < GO_REAL_EPSILON) {
1499  if (NULL != result) *result = GO_RESULT_DIV_ERROR;
1500  return z2c;
1501  }
1502 
1503  z2c.re = z2.re, z2c.im = -z2.im; /* complex conjugate */
1504  if (NULL != result) *result = GO_RESULT_OK;
1505  return go_complex_scale(go_complex_mult(z1, z2c), 1.0 / denom);
1506  }

1511  }

1518  s.im = scale * z.im;

1526  }

1529  {

1531  }

1534  {

1536  }

1538  /*
1539  go_complex_sqrt() and go_complex_cbrt() are structured so that if
1540  the roots of complex conjugates are taken, the first roots z1 will
1541  be complex conjugates. This is due to atan2 returning args in the
1542  range -PI to PI.
1543  */
1544 
1545  void go_complex_sqrt(go_complex z, go_complex * z1, go_complex * z2)
1546  {
1547  go_real r, th;
1548 
1549  r = sqrt(go_complex_mag(z));
1550  th = 0.5 * go_complex_arg(z);
1551 
1552  z1->re = r * cos(th);
1553  z1->im = r * sin(th);
1554  if (NULL != z2) {
1555  z2->re = -z1->re;
1556  z2->im = -z1->im;
1557  }
1558 
1559  return;
1560  }
1561 
1562  void go_complex_cbrt(go_complex z, go_complex * z1, go_complex * z2, go_complex * z3)
1563  {
1564  go_real r, th;
1565 
1566  r = go_cbrt(go_complex_mag(z));
1567  th = 1.0/3.0 * go_complex_arg(z);
1568 
1569  z1->re = r * cos(th);
1570  z1->im = r * sin(th);
1571  if (NULL != z2) {
1572  z2->re = r * cos(th + 2.0/3.0 * GO_PI);
1573  z2->im = r * sin(th + 2.0/3.0 * GO_PI);
1574  }
1575  if (NULL != z3) {
1576  z3->re = r * cos(th + 4.0/3.0 * GO_PI);
1577  z3->im = r * sin(th + 4.0/3.0 * GO_PI);
1578  }
1579 
1580  return;
1581  }

1583  go_result go_quadratic_solve(const go_quadratic * quad,
1584  go_complex * z1,
1585  go_complex * z2)
1586  {
1587  go_real discr;
1588 
1589  /* check if b is 0 and we can reduce order */
1590  if (GO_SMALL(quad->b)) {
1591  z2->re = z2->im = 0.0;
1592  z1->re = -quad->a;
1593  z1->im = 0.0;
1594  return GO_RESULT_OK;
1595  }
1596 
1597  discr = go_sq(quad->a) - 4.0 * quad->b;
1598  if (discr < 0.0) {
1599  discr = sqrt(-discr);
1600  z1->re = z2->re = -0.5 * quad->a;
1601  z1->im = 0.5 * discr;
1602  z2->im = -0.5 * discr;
1603  } else {
1604  discr = sqrt(discr);
1605  z1->re = 0.5 * (-quad->a + discr);
1606  z2->re = 0.5 * (-quad->a - discr);
1607  z1->im = z2->im = 0.0;
1608  }
1609 
1610  return GO_RESULT_OK;
1611  }
1612 
1613  /*
1614  References on solving the cubic:
1615 
1616  "Solving Cubic and Quartic Polynomials,"
1617  www.karlscalculus.org/pdf/cubicQuartic.pdf
1618 
1619  "Cubic Equations in One Formula,"
1620  http://mathforum.org/library/drmath/view/52668.html
1621  */
1622  go_result go_cubic_solve(const go_cubic * cub,
1623  go_complex * z1,
1624  go_complex * z2,
1625  go_complex * z3)
1626  {
1627  go_quadratic quad;
1628  go_real a, b;
1629  go_complex z, A, B, I = {0.0, 1.0};
1630  go_complex u1, u2, u3;
1631 
1632  /* check if c is 0, and we have a root of 0 and can reduce order
1633  to a quadratic */
1634  if (GO_SMALL(cub->c)) {
1635  z3->re = z3->im = 0.0;
1636  quad.a = cub->a;
1637  quad.b = cub->b;
1638  return go_quadratic_solve(&quad, z1, z2);
1639  }
1640 
1641  a = cub->b - 1.0/3.0 * go_sq(cub->a);
1642  b = cub->c - 1.0/3.0 * cub->a * cub->b + 2.0/27.0 * go_cub(cub->a);
1643  z.re = 0.25 * go_sq(b) + 1.0/27.0 * go_cub(a), z.im = 0.0;
1644  go_complex_sqrt(z, &A, &B);
1645 
1646  /* since z is real, the pair of sqrt(z) is either pure real or
1647  pure complex */
1648  A.re -= 0.5 * b;
1649  B.re -= 0.5 * b;
1650  /* subtracting b/2 keeps them pure real and in general unequal, or
1651  makes them complex conjugates */
1652 
1653  /* Now we need to take the cube root of each. If they're pure real,
1654  we can take the scalar cube root. */
1655  if (GO_SMALL(A.im)) {
1656  A.re = go_cbrt(A.re), A.im = 0.0;
1657  B.re = go_cbrt(B.re), B.im = 0.0;
1658  } else {
1659  go_complex_cbrt(A, &A, NULL, NULL);
1660  B.re = A.re, B.im = -A.im; /* B and A must be complex conjugates */
1661  }
1662  u1 = go_complex_add(A, B);
1663  u2 = u3 = go_complex_scale(u1, -0.5);
1664  z = go_complex_scale(go_complex_sub(A, B), sqrt(0.75));
1665  z = go_complex_mult(I, z);
1666  u2 = go_complex_add(u2, z);
1667  u3 = go_complex_sub(u3, z);
1668 
1669  z1->re = u1.re - 1.0/3.0 * cub->a, z1->im = u1.im;
1670  z2->re = u2.re - 1.0/3.0 * cub->a, z2->im = u2.im;
1671  z3->re = u3.re - 1.0/3.0 * cub->a, z3->im = u3.im;
1672 
1673  return GO_RESULT_OK;
1674  }
1675 
1676  go_result go_quartic_solve(const go_quartic * quart,
1677  go_complex * z1,
1678  go_complex * z2,
1679  go_complex * z3,
1680  go_complex * z4)
1681  {
1682  go_cubic cub;
1683  go_quadratic quad;
1684  go_real a2, a3, a4;
1685  go_real e, f, g;
1686  go_real mag1, mag2, mag3;
1687  go_complex p, q, r;
1688  go_complex biga, bigb;
1689  go_result retval;
1690 
1691  gocode = 0;
1692 
1693  /*
1694  There are several ways to solve quartic equations. They all start by
1695  dividing the equation by the leading coefficient, to make it of the
1696  form
1697 
1698  x4 + a x3 + b x2 + c x + d = 0.
1699 
1700  There is an easy special case if d = 0, in which case you can factor
1701  the quartic into x times a cubic. The roots then are 0 and the roots
1702  of that cubic. (To solve the cubic equation, see above.)
1703  */
1704  if (GO_SMALL(quart->d)) {
1705  /* set one root to be 0 and solve for reduced cubic */
1706  z4->re = z4->im = 0.0;
1707  cub.a = quart->a;
1708  cub.b = quart->b;
1709  cub.c = quart->c;
1710 
1711  gocode = 1;
1712 
1713  return go_cubic_solve(&cub, z1, z2, z3);
1714  }
1715 
1716  /*
1717  First eliminate the third-order term. Substitute x = y - a/4,
1718  expand, and simplify, to get
1719 
1720  y4 + e y2 + f y + g = 0
1721 
1722  where
1723 
1724  e = b - 3 a2/8,
1725  f = c + a3/8 - a b/2,
1726  g = d - 3 a4/256 + a2 b/16 - a c/4.
1727  */
1728  a2 = go_sq(quart->a);
1729  e = quart->b - 3.0/8.0 * a2;
1730  a3 = a2 * quart->a;
1731  f = quart->c + 1.0/8.0 * a3 - 0.5 * (quart->a * quart->b);
1732  a4 = a2 * a2;
1733  g = quart->d - 3.0/256.0 * a4 + 1.0/16.0 * a2 * quart->b - 0.25 * (quart->a * quart->c);
1734  /*
1735  At this point, there are two useful special cases.
1736 
1737  1. If g = 0, then, again, you can factor the quartic into y times
1738  a cubic. The roots of the original equation are then x = -a/4
1739  and the roots of that cubic with a/4 subtracted from each.
1740 
1741  2. If f = 0, then the quartic in y is actually a quadratic
1742  equation in the variable y2. Solve this using your favorite
1743  method, and then take the two square roots of each of the
1744  solutions for y2 to find the four values of y which
1745  work. Subtract a/4 from each to get the four roots x.
1746 
1747  Henceforth we can assume that d, f, and g are all nonzero.
1748  */
1749  /* Case 1 */
1750  if (GO_SMALL(g)) {
1751  a4 = -0.25 * quart->a; /* reuse a4 as -a/4, save a var */
1752  z4->re = a4;
1753  z4->im = 0.0;
1754  cub.a = 0.0;
1755  cub.b = e;
1756  cub.c = f;
1757  retval = go_cubic_solve(&cub, z1, z2, z3);
1758  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
1759  z1->re += a4;
1760  z2->re += a4;
1761  z3->re += a4;
1762 
1763  gocode = 2;
1764 
1765  return GO_RESULT_OK;
1766  }
1767  /* Case 2 */
1768  if (GO_SMALL(f)) {
1769  a4 = -0.25 * quart->a; /* reuse a4 as -a/4, save a var */
1770  quad.a = e;
1771  quad.b = g;
1772  retval = go_quadratic_solve(&quad, z1, z3);
1773  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
1774  go_complex_sqrt(*z1, z1, z2);
1775  go_complex_sqrt(*z3, z3, z4);
1776  z1->re += a4;
1777  z2->re += a4;
1778  z3->re += a4;
1779  z4->re += a4;
1780 
1781  gocode = 3;
1782 
1783  return GO_RESULT_OK;
1784  }
1785 
1786  /*
1787  Here is one way to proceed from this point. The related auxiliary
1788  cubic equation
1789 
1790  z3 + (e/2) z2 + ((e2-4 g)/16) z - f2/64 = 0
1791 
1792  has three roots. Find those roots by solving this cubic (again,
1793  see above). None of these is zero because f isn't zero. Let p and
1794  q be the square roots of two of those roots (any choices of roots
1795  and signs will work), and set
1796 
1797  r = -f/(8 p q).
1798 
1799  Then p2, q2, and r2 are the three roots of the above cubic. More
1800  important is the fact that the four roots of the original quartic
1801  are
1802 
1803  x = p + q + r - a/4,
1804  x = p - q - r - a/4,
1805  x = -p + q - r - a/4, and
1806  x = -p - q + r - a/4.
1807 
1808  This solution was discovered by Leonhard Euler (1707-1783).
1809  */
1810  cub.a = 0.5 * e;
1811  cub.b = 1.0/16.0 * (go_sq(e) - 4.0 * g);
1812  cub.c = -1.0/64.0 * go_sq(f);
1813  retval = go_cubic_solve(&cub, z1, z2, z3);
1814  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
1815 
1816  /* pick the two biggest roots */
1817  mag1 = go_complex_magsq(*z1);
1818  mag2 = go_complex_magsq(*z2);
1819  mag3 = go_complex_magsq(*z3);
1820  if (mag1 > mag2) {
1821  biga = *z1;
1822  if (mag2 > mag3) {
1823  bigb = *z2;
1824  } else {
1825  bigb = *z3;
1826  }
1827  } else {
1828  biga = *z2;
1829  if (mag1 > mag3) {
1830  bigb = *z1;
1831  } else {
1832  bigb = *z3;
1833  }
1834  }
1835 
1836  go_complex_sqrt(biga, &p, NULL);
1837  go_complex_sqrt(bigb, &q, NULL);
1838  r = go_complex_inv(go_complex_scale(go_complex_mult(p, q), -8.0/f), &retval);
1839  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
1840 
1841  a4 = 0.25 * quart->a;
1842  *z1 = go_complex_add(go_complex_add(p, q), r);
1843  z1->re -= a4;
1844  *z2 = go_complex_sub(go_complex_sub(p, q), r);
1845  z2->re -= a4;
1846  *z3 = go_complex_sub(go_complex_sub(q, p), r);
1847  z3->re -= a4;
1848  *z4 = go_complex_sub(go_complex_sub(r, p), q);
1849  z4->re -= a4;
1850 
1851  gocode = 4;
1852 
1853  return GO_RESULT_OK;
1854  }

1856 #define SIGN(a,b) ((b) >= 0.0 ? fabs(a) : -fabs(a))
1857 #define MAG2(a,b) sqrt((a)*(a)+(b)*(b))
1858 
1867  go_result go_tridiag_reduce(go_real **a, /*< the real symmetric matrix,
1868  overwritten with the diagonalizing
1869  matrix */
1870  go_integer n, /*< how many rows and columns */
1871  go_real *d, /*< the diagonal elements will be
1872  stored here */
1873  go_real *e) /*< the off-diagonal elements
1874  will be stored here, starting
1875  at index 1 */
1876  {
1877  go_integer l,k,j,i;
1878  go_real scale,hh,h,g,f;
1879 
1880  for (i=n-1;i>0;i--) {
1881  l=i-1;
1882  h=scale=0.0;
1883  if (l > 0) {
1884  for (k=0;k<=l;k++)
1885  scale += fabs(a[i][k]);
1886  if (scale == 0.0)
1887  e[i]=a[i][l];
1888  else {
1889  for (k=0;k<=l;k++) {
1890  a[i][k] /= scale;
1891  h += a[i][k]*a[i][k];
1892  }
1893  f=a[i][l];
1894  g=(f >= 0.0 ? -sqrt(h) : sqrt(h));
1895  e[i]=scale*g;
1896  h -= f*g;
1897  a[i][l]=f-g;
1898  f=0.0;
1899  for (j=0;j<=l;j++) {
1900  a[j][i]=a[i][j]/h;
1901  g=0.0;
1902  for (k=0;k<=j;k++)
1903  g += a[j][k]*a[i][k];
1904  for (k=j+1;k<=l;k++)
1905  g += a[k][j]*a[i][k];
1906  e[j]=g/h;
1907  f += e[j]*a[i][j];
1908  }
1909  hh=f/(h+h);
1910  for (j=0;j<=l;j++) {
1911  f=a[i][j];
1912  e[j]=g=e[j]-hh*f;
1913  for (k=0;k<=j;k++)
1914  a[j][k] -= (f*e[k]+g*a[i][k]);
1915  }
1916  }
1917  } else
1918  e[i]=a[i][l];
1919  d[i]=h;
1920  }
1921  d[0]=0.0;
1922  e[0]=0.0;
1923  for (i=0;i<n;i++) {
1924  l=i-1;
1925  if (d[i]) {
1926  for (j=0;j<=l;j++) {
1927  g=0.0;
1928  for (k=0;k<=l;k++)
1929  g += a[i][k]*a[k][j];
1930  for (k=0;k<=l;k++)
1931  a[k][j] -= g*a[k][i];
1932  }
1933  }
1934  d[i]=a[i][i];
1935  a[i][i]=1.0;
1936  for (j=0;j<=l;j++) a[j][i]=a[i][j]=0.0;
1937  }
1938 
1939  return GO_RESULT_OK;
1940  }
1941 
1957  go_result go_tridiag_ql(go_real *d,
1958  go_real *e,
1959  go_integer n,
1960  go_real **z)
1961  {
1962  go_integer m,l,iter,i,k;
1963  go_real s,r,p,g,f,dd,c,b;
1964 
1965  for (i=1;i<n;i++) e[i-1]=e[i];
1966  e[n-1]=0.0;
1967  for (l=0;l<n;l++) {
1968  iter=0;
1969  do {
1970  for (m=l;m<n-1;m++) {
1971  dd=fabs(d[m])+fabs(d[m+1]);
1972  if ((go_real)(fabs(e[m])+dd) == dd) break;
1973  }
1974  if (m != l) {
1975  if (iter++ == 30) return GO_RESULT_ERROR;
1976  g=(d[l+1]-d[l])/(2.0*e[l]);
1977  r=MAG2(g,1.0);
1978  g=d[m]-d[l]+e[l]/(g+SIGN(r,g));
1979  s=c=1.0;
1980  p=0.0;
1981  for (i=m-1;i>=l;i--) {
1982  f=s*e[i];
1983  b=c*e[i];
1984  e[i+1]=(r=MAG2(f,g));
1985  if (r == 0.0) {
1986  d[i+1] -= p;
1987  e[m]=0.0;
1988  break;
1989  }
1990  s=f/r;
1991  c=g/r;
1992  g=d[i+1]-p;
1993  r=(d[i]-g)*s+2.0*c*b;
1994  d[i+1]=g+(p=s*r);
1995  g=c*r-b;
1996  for (k=0;k<n;k++) {
1997  f=z[k][i+1];
1998  z[k][i+1]=s*z[k][i]+c*f;
1999  z[k][i]=c*z[k][i]-s*f;
2000  }
2001  }
2002  if (r == 0.0 && i >= l) continue;
2003  d[l] -= p;
2004  e[l]=g;
2005  e[m]=0.0;
2006  }
2007  } while (m != l);
2008  }
2009 
2010  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2011  }

2013  /*
2014  Implements Berthold K. P. Horn's solution to the absolute
2015  orientation problem, which is:
2016 
2017  Given a relatively large set of points, and two sets of measurements
2018  of the Cartesian XYZ location of these points with respect to two
2019  coordinate systems, what is the least-squares best fit transform
2020  from one coordinate system to the other?
2021 
2022  See Berthold K. P. Horn, "Close-form solution of absolute
2023  orientation using unit quaternions," Journal of the Optical Society
2024  of America A, Vol. 4, page 629, April 1987.
2025  */
2026  go_result go_cart_cart_pose(const go_cart *v1,
2027  const go_cart *v2,
2028  go_cart *v1c,
2029  go_cart *v2c,
2030  go_integer num,
2031  go_pose *pout)
2032  {
2033  go_integer t;
2034  go_cart c1, c2;
2035  go_real Sxx, Sxy, Sxz;
2036  go_real Syx, Syy, Syz;
2037  go_real Szx, Szy, Szz;
2038  GO_MATRIX_DECLARE(N, Nspace, 4, 4);
2039  go_real d[4], e[4];
2040  go_real eigenval;
2041  go_result retval;
2042 
2043  Sxx = Sxy = Sxz = 0.0;
2044  Syx = Syy = Syz = 0.0;
2045  Szx = Szy = Szz = 0.0;
2046 
2047  go_matrix_init(N, Nspace, 4, 4);
2048 
2049  retval = go_cart_centroidize(v1, num, &c1, v1c);
2050  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2051  retval = go_cart_centroidize(v2, num, &c2, v2c);
2052  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2053 
2054  for (t = 0; t < num; t++) {
2055  Sxx += v1c[t].x * v2c[t].x;
2056  Sxy += v1c[t].x * v2c[t].y;
2057  Sxz += v1c[t].x * v2c[t].z;
2058 
2059  Syx += v1c[t].y * v2c[t].x;
2060  Syy += v1c[t].y * v2c[t].y;
2061  Syz += v1c[t].y * v2c[t].z;
2062 
2063  Szx += v1c[t].z * v2c[t].x;
2064  Szy += v1c[t].z * v2c[t].y;
2065  Szz += v1c[t].z * v2c[t].z;
2066  }
2067 
2068  N.el[0][0] = Sxx + Syy + Szz;
2069  N.el[0][1] = N.el[1][0] = Syz - Szy;
2070  N.el[0][2] = N.el[2][0] = Szx - Sxz;
2071  N.el[0][3] = N.el[3][0] = Sxy - Syx;
2072 
2073  N.el[1][1] = Sxx - Syy - Szz;
2074  N.el[1][2] = N.el[2][1] = Sxy + Syx;
2075  N.el[1][3] = N.el[3][1] = Szx + Sxz;
2076 
2077  N.el[2][2] = -Sxx + Syy - Szz;
2078  N.el[2][3] = N.el[3][2] = Syz + Szy;
2079 
2080  N.el[3][3] = -Sxx -Syy + Szz;
2081 
2082  /* compute eigenvectors */
2083  retval = go_tridiag_reduce(N.el, 4, d, e);
2084  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2085  retval = go_tridiag_ql(d, e, 4, N.el);
2086  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2087 
2088  /* pick eigenvector associated with most positive eigenvalue */
2089  eigenval = d[0], t = 0;
2090  if (d[1] > eigenval) eigenval = d[1], t = 1;
2091  if (d[2] > eigenval) eigenval = d[2], t = 2;
2092  if (d[3] > eigenval) eigenval = d[3], t = 3;
2093  /* now t is the column with the eigenvector we want as our quaternion */
2094  pout->rot.s = N.el[0][t];
2095  pout->rot.x = N.el[1][t];
2096  pout->rot.y = N.el[2][t];
2097  pout->rot.z = N.el[3][t];
2098  retval = go_quat_norm(&pout->rot, &pout->rot);
2099  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2100 
2101  /* rotate left centroid, subtract left from right to get translation */
2102  (void) go_quat_cart_mult(&pout->rot, &c1, &c1);
2103  (void) go_cart_cart_sub(&c2, &c1, &pout->tran);
2104 
2105  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2106  }

2108  static go_result trilaterate(go_real x2, go_real x3, go_real y3,
2109  go_real l1, go_real l2, go_real l3,
2110  go_cart *p)
2111  {
2112  go_real discr;
2113 
2114  p->x = 0.5 * (x2 - (go_sq(l2) - go_sq(l1))/x2);
2115 
2116  p->y =
2117  (go_sq(l1) - 2.0 * p->x * x3 + go_sq(x3) +
2118  go_sq(y3) - go_sq(l3)) / (2.0 * y3);
2119 
2120  discr = go_sq(l1) - go_sq(p->x) - go_sq(p->y);
2121  if (discr < -GO_REAL_EPSILON) {
2122  return GO_RESULT_DOMAIN_ERROR;
2123  }
2124  if (discr < 0.0) discr = 0.0; /* make slightly negative numbers 0 */
2125 
2126  /* return z positive, caller can make negative if they want the
2127  point below the base */
2128  p->z = sqrt(discr);
2129 
2130  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2131  }

2133  go_result go_cart_trilaterate(const go_cart *c1,
2134  const go_cart *c2,
2135  const go_cart *c3,
2136  go_real l1,
2137  go_real l2,
2138  go_real l3,
2139  go_cart *out1,
2140  go_cart *out2)
2141  {
2142  go_pose P_to_B, B_to_P;
2143  go_mat mat;
2144  go_cart diff, proj;
2145  go_cart p1, p2, p3, out1_in_P, out2_in_P;
2146  go_result retval;
2147 
2148  /* transform the points from their original base frame {B} into an
2149  easier frame {P}, with c1 at the {P}, origin, c2 along the {P} x
2150  axis, and all three in the {P} xy plane */
2151 
2152  /* first get the transform */
2153  P_to_B.tran = *c1;
2154  go_cart_cart_sub(c2, c1, &diff);
2155  retval = go_cart_unit(&diff, &mat.x);
2156  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2157  go_cart_cart_sub(c3, c1, &diff);
2158  retval = go_cart_cart_proj(&diff, &mat.x, &proj);
2159  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2160  go_cart_cart_sub(&diff, &proj, &diff);
2161  retval = go_cart_unit(&diff, &mat.y);
2162  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2163  go_cart_cart_cross(&mat.x, &mat.y, &mat.z);
2164  retval = go_mat_quat_convert(&mat, &P_to_B.rot);
2165  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2166  retval = go_pose_inv(&P_to_B, &B_to_P);
2167  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2168  /* now transform them */
2169  go_pose_cart_mult(&B_to_P, c1, &p1);
2170  go_pose_cart_mult(&B_to_P, c2, &p2);
2171  go_pose_cart_mult(&B_to_P, c3, &p3);
2172 
2173  /* trilaterate to get the point in {P} */
2174  retval = trilaterate(p2.x, p3.x, p3.y, l1, l2, l3, &out1_in_P);
2175  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2176  out2_in_P.x = out1_in_P.x;
2177  out2_in_P.y = out1_in_P.y;
2178  out2_in_P.z = -out1_in_P.z; /* the other one has a minus z */
2179  go_pose_cart_mult(&P_to_B, &out1_in_P, out1);
2180  go_pose_cart_mult(&P_to_B, &out2_in_P, out2);
2181 
2182  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2183  }

2383  qout->z = -q1->z * size;
2384 
2385  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2386  }
2387  }
2388 
2389  go_result go_quat_inv(const go_quat *q1, go_quat *qout)
2390  {
2391  qout->s = q1->s;
2392  qout->x = -q1->x;
2393  qout->y = -q1->y;
2394  qout->z = -q1->z;
2395 
2396  if (!go_quat_is_norm(q1)) {
2397  return GO_RESULT_NORM_ERROR;
2398  }
2399 
2400  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2401  }
2402 
2403  go_flag go_quat_is_norm(const go_quat *q1)
2404  {
2405  return GO_TRAN_CLOSE(go_sq(q1->s) +
2406  go_sq(q1->x) +
2407  go_sq(q1->y) +
2408  go_sq(q1->z), 1);
2409  }
2410 
2411  go_result go_quat_scale_mult(const go_quat *q, go_real s, go_quat *qout)
2412  {
2413  go_real sh; /* sine of half angle */
2414  go_real ha; /* half angle */
2415  go_real scale; /* new sh / old sh */
2416 
2417  sh = sqrt(go_sq(q->x) + go_sq(q->y) + go_sq(q->z));
2418  if (GO_SMALL(sh)) {
2419  /* zero rotation-- leave it alone */
2420  *qout = *q;
2421  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2422  }
2423 
2424  ha = atan2(sh, q->s);
2425  ha *= s;
2426  scale = sin(ha) / sh;
2427 
2428  qout->s = cos(ha);
2429  qout->x = scale * q->x;
2430  qout->y = scale * q->y;
2431  qout->z = scale * q->z;
2432 
2433  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2434  }
2435 
2436  go_result go_quat_quat_mult(const go_quat *q1, const go_quat *q2,
2437  go_quat *qout)
2438  {
2439  go_quat cp1, cp2;
2440 
2441  if (!go_quat_is_norm(q1) || !go_quat_is_norm(q2)) {
2442  return GO_RESULT_NORM_ERROR;
2443  }
2444 
2445  cp1 = *q1;
2446  cp2 = *q2;
2447 
2448  qout->s = cp1.s * cp2.s - cp1.x * cp2.x - cp1.y * cp2.y - cp1.z * cp2.z;
2449 
2450  if (qout->s >= 0) {
2451  qout->x = cp1.s * cp2.x + cp1.x * cp2.s + cp1.y * cp2.z - cp1.z * cp2.y;
2452  qout->y = cp1.s * cp2.y - cp1.x * cp2.z + cp1.y * cp2.s + cp1.z * cp2.x;
2453  qout->z = cp1.s * cp2.z + cp1.x * cp2.y - cp1.y * cp2.x + cp1.z * cp2.s;
2454  } else {
2455  qout->s = -qout->s;
2456  qout->x = -cp1.s * cp2.x - cp1.x * cp2.s - cp1.y * cp2.z + cp1.z * cp2.y;
2457  qout->y = -cp1.s * cp2.y + cp1.x * cp2.z - cp1.y * cp2.s - cp1.z * cp2.x;
2458  qout->z = -cp1.s * cp2.z - cp1.x * cp2.y + cp1.y * cp2.x - cp1.z * cp2.s;
2459  }
2460 
2461  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2462  }
2463 
2464  go_result go_quat_cart_mult(const go_quat *q1, const go_cart *v2,
2465  go_cart *vout)
2466  {
2467  go_cart c;
2468 
2469  if (!go_quat_is_norm(q1)) {
2470  return GO_RESULT_NORM_ERROR;
2471  }
2472 
2473  c.x = q1->y * v2->z - q1->z * v2->y;
2474  c.y = q1->z * v2->x - q1->x * v2->z;
2475  c.z = q1->x * v2->y - q1->y * v2->x;
2476 
2477  vout->x = v2->x + 2 * (q1->s * c.x + q1->y * c.z - q1->z * c.y);
2478  vout->y = v2->y + 2 * (q1->s * c.y + q1->z * c.x - q1->x * c.z);
2479  vout->z = v2->z + 2 * (q1->s * c.z + q1->x * c.y - q1->y * c.x);
2480 
2481  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2482  }

2489  go_cart_cart_compare(&p1->tran, &p2->tran));

2492  go_result go_pose_inv(const go_pose *p1, go_pose *p2)
2493  {
2494  go_result retval;
2495 
2496  retval = go_quat_inv(&p1->rot, &p2->rot);
2497  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2498 
2499  retval = go_quat_cart_mult(&p2->rot, &p1->tran, &p2->tran);
2500  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2501 
2502  p2->tran.x = -p2->tran.x;
2503  p2->tran.y = -p2->tran.y;
2504  p2->tran.z = -p2->tran.z;
2505

2507  }

2509  go_result go_pose_cart_mult(const go_pose *p1, const go_cart *v2, go_cart *vout)
2510  {
2511  go_result retval;
2512 
2513  /* first rotate the vector */
2514  retval = go_quat_cart_mult(&p1->rot, v2, vout);
2515  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2516 
2517  /* then translate it */
2518  return go_cart_cart_add(&p1->tran, vout, vout);
2519  }
2520 
2521  /*
2522  go_pose_pose_mult() implements compound transforms,
2523 
2524  0 0 1
2525  .T = T * T
2526  2 1 2
2527 
2528  Expressed in terms of individual position vectors P and rotations R,
2529 
2530  0 0 1
2531  .R = R * R
2532  2 1 2
2533 
2534  0 0 0 1
2535  .P = P + R * P
2536  2 1 1 2
2537 
2538  This would be called as go_pose_pose_mult(&T_1_0, &T_2_1, &T_2_0).
2539  */
2540 
2541  go_result go_pose_pose_mult(const go_pose *p1, const go_pose *p2, go_pose *pout)
2542  {
2543  go_pose out;
2544  go_result retval;
2545 
2546  retval = go_quat_cart_mult(&p1->rot, &p2->tran, &out.tran);
2547  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2548 
2549  retval = go_cart_cart_add(&p1->tran, &out.tran, &out.tran);
2550  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2551 
2552  retval = go_quat_quat_mult(&p1->rot, &p2->rot, &out.rot);
2553 
2554  *pout = out;
2555 
2556  return retval;
2557  }

2560  {
2561  (void) go_cart_scale_mult(&p1->tran, s, &pout->tran);
2562  return go_quat_scale_mult(&p1->rot, s, &pout->rot);
2563  }

2565  go_result go_pose_pose_interp(go_real t1, const go_pose *p1, go_real t2, const go_pose *p2, go_real t3, go_pose *p3)
2566  {
2567  go_pose pdiff;
2568  go_result retval;
2569 
2570  if (GO_CLOSE(t1, t2)) return GO_RESULT_ERROR;
2571 
2572  retval = go_pose_inv(p1, &pdiff);
2573  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2574

2576  (void) go_pose_scale_mult(&pdiff, (t3 - t1) / (t2 - t1), &pdiff);
2577  return go_pose_pose_mult(p1, &pdiff, p3);
2578  }

2617  go_result go_pose_vel_mult(const go_pose *pose, const go_vel *vel, go_vel *out)
2618  {
2619  go_pose poseinv;
2620  go_cart wxp;
2621  go_cart v;
2622  go_result retval;
2623 
2624  /*
2625  B |B . B |
2626  .T = | R . P |
2627  A |A . A|
2628 
2629  B B A A A
2630  .v = R ( v + w X P )
2631  . A B
2632 
2633  B B A
2634  .w = R w
2635  . A
2636  */
2637 
2638  retval = go_pose_inv(pose, &poseinv);
2639  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
2640 
2641  go_cart_cart_cross(&vel->w, &poseinv.tran, &wxp);
2642  go_cart_cart_add(&vel->v, &wxp, &v);
2643  go_quat_cart_mult(&pose->rot, &v, &out->v);
2644  go_quat_cart_mult(&pose->rot, &vel->w, &out->w);
2645 
2646  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2647  }

2677  go_result go_line_from_planes(const go_plane *plane1, const go_plane *plane2, go_line *line)
2678  {
2679  enum {X, Y, Z} which;
2680  go_real max, ymax, denominv;
2681 
2682  (void) go_cart_cart_cross(&plane1->normal, &plane2->normal, &line->direction);
2683  if (GO_RESULT_OK != go_cart_unit(&line->direction, &line->direction)) {
2684  /* planes are parallel */
2685  return GO_RESULT_ERROR;
2686  }
2687 
2688  /* pick the cross product component with the largest magnitude,
2689  which will give the most robust calculations for the point
2690  on the line */
2691  max = fabs(line->direction.x);
2692  which = X;
2693  ymax = fabs(line->direction.y);
2694  if (ymax > max) {
2695  max = ymax;
2696  which = Y;
2697  }
2698  if (fabs(line->direction.z) > max) {
2699  which = Z;
2700  }
2701 
2702  switch (which) {
2703  case X:
2704  denominv = 1.0/(plane1->normal.y*plane2->normal.z -
2705  plane2->normal.y*plane1->normal.z);
2706  line->point.y = (plane1->normal.z*plane2->d -
2707  plane2->normal.z*plane1->d)*denominv;
2708  line->point.z = (plane2->normal.y*plane1->d -
2709  plane1->normal.y*plane2->d)*denominv;
2710  line->point.x = 0;
2711  break;
2712  case Y:
2713  denominv = 1.0/(plane1->normal.z*plane2->normal.x -
2714  plane2->normal.z*plane1->normal.x);
2715  line->point.z = (plane1->normal.x*plane2->d -
2716  plane2->normal.x*plane1->d)*denominv;
2717  line->point.x = (plane2->normal.z*plane1->d -
2718  plane1->normal.z*plane2->d)*denominv;
2719  line->point.y = 0;
2720  break;
2721  default:
2722  denominv = 1.0/(plane1->normal.x*plane2->normal.y -
2723  plane2->normal.x*plane1->normal.y);
2724  line->point.x = (plane1->normal.y*plane2->d -
2725  plane2->normal.y*plane1->d)*denominv;
2726  line->point.y = (plane2->normal.x*plane1->d -
2727  plane1->normal.x*plane2->d)*denominv;
2728  line->point.z = 0;
2729  break;
2730  }
2731 
2732  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2733  }
2734 
2735  go_flag go_line_line_compare(const go_line *line1, const go_line *line2)
2736  {
2737  go_cart diff;
2738  go_real dot;
2739 
2740  /* check that directions are parallel */
2741  go_cart_cart_dot(&line1->direction, &line2->direction, &dot);
2742  if (! GO_CLOSE(dot, 1)) return 0;
2743 
2744  /* check that points are along the direction */
2745  (void) go_cart_cart_sub(&line1->point, &line2->point, &diff);
2746  go_cart_cart_dot(&line1->direction, &diff, &dot);
2747  if (! GO_CLOSE(dot, 1)) return 0;
2748 
2749  return 1;
2750  }

2767  go_sq(line->direction.x * (point->z - line->point.z) -
2768  line->direction.z * (point->x - line->point.x)) +
2769  go_sq(line->direction.y * (point->x - line->point.x) -

2788  go_result go_point_plane_proj(const go_cart *point, const go_plane *plane, go_cart *proj)
2789  {
2790  go_real denom;
2791  go_real k;
2792 
2793  denom =
2794  go_sq(plane->normal.x) +
2795  go_sq(plane->normal.y) +
2796  go_sq(plane->normal.z);
2797 
2798  if (GO_TRAN_SMALL(denom)) return GO_RESULT_DIV_ERROR;
2799 
2800  k = -(plane->normal.x * point->x +
2801  plane->normal.y * point->y +
2802  plane->normal.z * point->z +
2803  plane->d)/denom;
2804 
2805  proj->x = point->x + k*plane->normal.x;
2806  proj->y = point->y + k*plane->normal.y;
2807  proj->z = point->z + k*plane->normal.z;
2808

2833  go_result go_plane_from_abcd(go_real A, go_real B, go_real C, go_real D, go_plane *plane)
2834  {
2835  go_real mag;
2836 
2837  /* get magnitude of normal vector, actually mag squared */
2838  mag = go_sq(A) + go_sq(B) + go_sq(C);
2839  if (GO_TRAN_SMALL(mag)) {
2840  return GO_RESULT_DIV_ERROR;
2841  }
2842  mag = 1.0 / sqrt(mag); /* now it's the mag multiplier */
2843 
2844  plane->normal.x = A * mag;
2845  plane->normal.y = B * mag;
2846  plane->normal.z = C * mag;
2847  plane->d = D * mag;
2848 
2849  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2850  }

2861  /* D = -(Ax + By + Cz) */
2862  plane->d = -(plane->normal.x * point1->x +
2863  plane->normal.y * point1->y +
2864  plane->normal.z * point1->z);

2897  go_result go_plane_evaluate(const go_plane *plane, go_real u, go_real v, go_cart *point)
2898  {
2899  go_cart v1, v2; /* othogonal vectors in plane */
2900  go_cart p; /* point in plane closest to origin */
2901 
2902  if (GO_RESULT_OK != go_cart_normal(&plane->normal, &v1)) return GO_RESULT_ERROR;
2903 
2904  (void) go_cart_cart_cross(&plane->normal, &v1, &v2);
2905  (void) go_cart_scale_mult(&v1, u, &v1);
2906  (void) go_cart_scale_mult(&v2, v, &v2);
2907 
2908  /* with point = k * normal,
2909  a*ka * y*ky + z*kz + d = 0,
2910  k*(1) + d = 0,
2911  k = -d
2912  */
2913  p.x = -plane->normal.x * plane->d;
2914  p.y = -plane->normal.y * plane->d;
2915  p.z = -plane->normal.z * plane->d;
2916 
2917  (void) go_cart_cart_add(&p, &v1, &p);
2918  (void) go_cart_cart_add(&p, &v2, point);
2919 
2920  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2921  }
2922 
2923  /*
2924  To get the intersect point of the line and plane, set them equal and
2925  solve for the line parameter d, then plug into the parameterization
2926  to get the point:
2927 
2928  A(px + d*vx) + B(py + d*vy) + C(pz + d*vz) + D = 0
2929 
2930  _ -(A*px + B*py + C*pz + D)
2931  d ---------------------
2932  _ A*vx + B*vy + C*vz
2933 
2934  Then plug d into px + d*vx, ... to get intersect x, y and z.
2935  */
2936  go_result go_line_plane_intersect(const go_line *line, const go_plane *plane, go_cart *point, go_real *distance)
2937  {
2938  go_real num, denom;
2939 
2940  /* first check for line parallel to plane */
2941  (void) go_cart_cart_dot(&plane->normal, &line->direction, &denom);
2942  if (GO_SMALL(denom)) return GO_RESULT_ERROR;
2943 
2944  /* check for point lying in plane */

2960  /*
2961  Adapted from ludcmp routine in Numerical Recipes in C, but with
2962  indices starting at 0 and no heap allocation.
2963 
2964  Given a matrix a[0..n-1][0..n-1], this routine replaces it by the LU
2965  decomposition of a rowwise permutation of itself. a and n are
2966  input. a is changed and output. indx[0..n-1] is an output vector
2967  that records the row permutation effected by the partial pivoting; d
2968  is output as +/-1 depending on whether the number of row
2969  interchanges was even or odd, respectively. This routine is used in
2970  combination with lubksb to solve linear equations or invert a
2971  matrix.
2972 
2973  Warning! The matrix 'a' can't be declared as go_real a[n][n]. It
2974  needs to be an array of go_real pointers. See e.g. go_mat6_inv() for
2975  how to set up the 'a' matrix.
2976  */
2977 
2978  static go_real go_singular_epsilon = 1.0e-15;
2979 
2980  go_real go_get_singular_epsilon(void)
2981  {
2982  return go_singular_epsilon;
2983  }
2984 
2985  go_result go_set_singular_epsilon(go_real epsilon)
2986  {
2987  if (epsilon <= 0.0) return GO_RESULT_ERROR;
2988 
2989  go_singular_epsilon = epsilon;
2990 
2991  return GO_RESULT_OK;
2992  }

2994  go_result ludcmp(go_real **a,
2995  go_real *scratchrow,
2996  go_integer n,
2997  go_integer * indx,
2998  go_real *d)
2999  {
3000  go_integer i, imax, j, k;
3001  go_real big, dum, sum, temp;
3002 
3003  *d = 1.0;
3004  for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
3005  big = 0.0;
3006  for (j = 0; j < n; j++)
3007  if ((temp = fabs(a[i][j])) > big)
3008  big = temp;
3009  if (big < go_singular_epsilon)
3010  return GO_RESULT_SINGULAR;
3011  scratchrow[i] = 1.0 / big;
3012  }
3013  for (j = 0; j < n; j++) {
3014  for (i = 0; i < j; i++) {
3015  sum = a[i][j];
3016  for (k = 0; k < i; k++)
3017  sum -= a[i][k] * a[k][j];
3018  a[i][j] = sum;
3019  }
3020  big = 0.0;
3021  imax = 0;
3022  for (i = j; i < n; i++) {
3023  sum = a[i][j];
3024  for (k = 0; k < j; k++)
3025  sum -= a[i][k] * a[k][j];
3026  a[i][j] = sum;
3027  if ((dum = scratchrow[i] * fabs(sum)) >= big) {
3028  big = dum;
3029  imax = i;
3030  }
3031  }
3032  if (j != imax) {
3033  for (k = 0; k < n; k++) {
3034  dum = a[imax][k];
3035  a[imax][k] = a[j][k];
3036  a[j][k] = dum;
3037  }
3038  *d = -(*d);
3039  scratchrow[imax] = scratchrow[j];
3040  }
3041  indx[j] = imax;
3042  if (fabs(a[j][j]) < go_singular_epsilon)
3043  return GO_RESULT_SINGULAR;
3044  if (j != n - 1) {
3045  dum = 1.0 / (a[j][j]);
3046  for (i = j + 1; i < n; i++)
3047  a[i][j] *= dum;
3048  }
3049  }
3050 
3051  return GO_RESULT_OK;
3052  }
3053 
3054  /*
3055  Solves the set of n linear equations AX = B. Here a[0..n-1][0..n-1]
3056  is input, not as the matrix A but rather as its LU decomposition,
3057  determined by the routine ludcmp. indx[0..n-1] is input as the
3058  permutation vector returned by ludcmp. b[0..n-1] is input as the
3059  right-hand side vector B, and returns with the solution vector X. a,
3060  n, and indx are not modified by this routine and can be left in
3061  place for successive calls with different right-hand sides b. This
3062  routine takes into account the possibility that b will begin with
3063  many zero elements, so it is efficient for use in matrix inversion.
3064 
3065  Warning! The matrix 'a' can't be declared as go_real a[n][n]. It
3066  needs to be an array of go_real pointers. See e.g. go_mat6_inv() for
3067  how to set up the 'a' matrix.
3068  */
3069 
3070  go_result lubksb(go_real **a,
3071  go_integer n,
3072  go_integer *indx,
3073  go_real *b)
3074  {
3075  go_integer i, ii = -1, ip, j;
3076  go_real sum;
3077 
3078  for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
3079  ip = indx[i];
3080  sum = b[ip];
3081  b[ip] = b[i];
3082  if (ii != -1)
3083  for (j = ii; j <= i - 1; j++)
3084  sum -= a[i][j] * b[j];
3085  else if (sum)
3086  ii = i;
3087  b[i] = sum;
3088  }
3089  for (i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
3090  sum = b[i];
3091  for (j = i + 1; j < n; j++)
3092  sum -= a[i][j] * b[j];
3093  if (fabs(a[i][i]) < go_singular_epsilon)
3094  return GO_RESULT_SINGULAR;
3095  b[i] = sum / a[i][i];
3096  }
3097 
3098  return GO_RESULT_OK;
3099  }

3859  go_result go_mat6_inv(go_real a[6][6],
3860  go_real ainv[6][6])
3861  {
3862  go_real cpy[6][6];
3863  go_real *cpyptr[6];
3864  go_real scratchrow[6];
3865  go_real v[6];
3866  go_real d;
3867  go_integer index[6];
3868  go_integer row, col;
3869  go_result retval;
3870 
3871  /* create a copy of m[][] in cpy[][], since ludcmp destroys input matrix */
3872  for (row = 0; row < 6; row++) {
3873  for (col = 0; col < 6; col++) {
3874  cpy[row][col] = a[row][col];
3875  }
3876  /* set up the go_real pointer array that ludcmp likes */
3877  cpyptr[row] = cpy[row];
3878  }
3879 
3880  /* convert the copy to its LU decomposition */
3881  retval = ludcmp(cpyptr, scratchrow, 6, index, &d);
3882  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
3883 
3884  /* backsubstitute a column with a 1 in it to get the inverse */
3885  for (col = 0; col < 6; col++) {
3886  for (row = 0; row < 6; row++) {
3887  v[row] = 0.0;
3888  }
3889  v[col] = 1.0;
3890  retval = lubksb(cpyptr, 6, index, v);
3891  if (GO_RESULT_OK != retval) return retval;
3892  for (row = 0; row < 6; row++) {
3893  ainv[row][col] = v[row];
3894  }
3895  }
3896 
3897  return GO_RESULT_OK;
3898  }

3962  go_result go_dh_hom_convert(const go_dh * dh, go_hom * h)
3963  {
3964  go_real sth, cth; /* sin, cos theta[i] */
3965  go_real sal, cal; /* sin, cos alpha[i-1] */
3966 
3967  go_sincos(dh->theta, &sth, &cth);
3968  go_sincos(dh->alpha, &sal, &cal);
3969 
3970  h->rot.x.x = cth, h->rot.y.x = -sth, h->rot.z.x = 0.0;
3971  h->rot.x.y = sth*cal, h->rot.y.y = cth*cal, h->rot.z.y = -sal;
3972  h->rot.x.z = sth*sal, h->rot.y.z = cth*sal, h->rot.z.z = cal;
3973 
3974  h->tran.x = dh->a;
3975  h->tran.y = -sal*dh->d;
3976  h->tran.z = cal*dh->d;
3977 
3978  return GO_RESULT_OK;
3979  }

4097  the identities
4098 
4099  cos theta = (1 - tan^2(theta/2)) / (1 + tan^2(theta/2))
4100  sin theta = 2 * tan(theta/2) / (1 + tan^2(theta/2))
4101 
4102  First normalize the equation so that the RHS is 1. Let T = tan(theta/2).
4103  Then,
4104 
4105  (-a-1) T^2 + 2b T + (a-1) = 0
4106 
4107  For a = -1, it degenerates, with solution
4108 
4109  T = Pi, atan2(2b/(b^2+1), (b^2-1)/(b^2+1))
4110 
4111  Otherwise it's quadratic; solve for both T solutions and finish
4112  by taking theta = 2 arctan(T). No real solutions if a^2 + b^2 < 1.
4113  */
4114  go_result go_linear_cos_sin_solve(go_real a, go_real b, go_real *th1, go_real *th2)
4115  {
4116  double d;
4117  double A, B, C;
4118 
4119  if (GO_ROT_CLOSE(a, -1)) {
4120  *th1 = GO_PI;
4121  d = b*b+1;
4122  *th2 = atan2(2*b/d, (b*b-1)/d);
4123  return GO_RESULT_OK;
4124  }
4125 
4126  A = -a-1, B = 2*b, C = a-1;
4127 
4128  d = B*B - 4*A*C;
4129  if (d < -GO_REAL_EPSILON) {
4130  return GO_RESULT_DOMAIN_ERROR;
4131  }
4132  if (d < 0.0) d = 0.0;
4133  d = sqrt(d);
4134  A = 0.5/A;
4135 
4136  *th1 = 2*atan((-B + d)*A);
4137  *th2 = 2*atan((-B - d)*A);
4138 
4139  return GO_RESULT_OK;
4140  }
4141 };
